@guozhangwang  @mjsax @dguy 
Please review when you have a chance.  

The previous change for multiple consumers missed extracting a block of code in the `topicGroups()` method only called for the leader `KafkaStreams` instance.

@junrao @ijuma @becketqin @onurkaraman So I looked into refactoring the `GroupCoordinator` so that the lock is not held when calling the purgatory. It's not clear to me that we do this safely without some restructuring (and rethinking). The difficulty is that we can make several calls to the purgatories while holding the lock and we seem to depend on the state of the group not changing in between calls. I don't know how we can reacquire the lock after releasing it unless we revalidate the current state of the group, which will make the patch fairly complicated. Maybe Onur could look and see whether there's an easier way, but I'm doubtful.

One alternative I was thinking about is whether we could use a different implementation of `Watchers` for the GroupCoordinator purgatories. For example, we could keep the old version as `Watchers`, and we could let the one included in this patch be `LockSafeWatchers` or something like that. What do you think?

For now, I've rebased the current patch.

Thanks for discovering the bug. In the case when we write a malformed message whose wrapper magic is different from the inner one, the impact seems to be the following: (1) the log cleaner will fail when it tries to read that message back since we validate the magic version btw inner and wrapper message in ByteBufferMessageSet.deepIterator(). (2) The old consumer will hit the same issue if it tries to read this malformed message. (3) It's not clear what happens to the new consumer since it doesn't seem that we validate the magic version btw inner and wrapper in MemoryRecords.

Now, on when this can be triggered. If this is the offset topic, since the consumer typically commits offsets for all assigned partitions together, chances are all messages in a compressed set will either be all cleaned and none will be cleaned. So, we we probably won't hit this case. KStream may use compacted topics. However, it's only available since 0.10, which uses magic version 1 already. So, it won't hit this issue either. So, the question is "are there any other common usage of compacted topic that can hit this issue".

@becketqin : Have you guys seen this issue at LinkedIn?
